\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Mr William East, 8 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Peabody{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Buildings{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}John Fisher Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, E1. He was married on November 30th 1919, and born 25th October 1897.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
I was born in Wapping and we lived there for one year, then we moved back to here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Can you remember the address where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes, Jubilee Buildings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 You said you lived only a year in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
In that - place, yes. Well me mother had to move out of here because she was overcrowded. We went to Jubilee Buildings, stopped there a year, and we come back here. I was the last one out of seven of us, 'cos all the others was getting married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 S
o really most of your life as a little boy that you remember was spent round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Boy. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
I had - Lizzie, she died, Lou, she died in the blitz, Ethel. Three sisters. John the oldest one, he's - a captain in the army. H}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 e was the eldest one, Charlie, }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Bert, six, seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 You were the youngest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 I was the youngest one of the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 How many years do you think there were between your brothers and sisters?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Well average say about - two years, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about your father, do you know how old he was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Well me father - 'cos we never used to take much notice of ages, but he worked in the dock - 'til he was sixty-five, and then he retired and bless his heart he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 When did he retire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh many years ago. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
You were the seventh child, I suppose he wasn't such a young man by the time you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Do you know where he came from, your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Well - he was local I believe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 He was a Londoner was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What did your father do for a living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 He was a dockie. A {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} dockie, he worked there for over forty years. He used to be - before that - he used to work at the Great Easter
n Biscuit. Yes. You know where the fire was. And - and after that he went in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} docks, and he was there forty - forty odd years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What sort of job did he do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 A labourer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 That's when he was at Bishopsgate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 On the bank there, working on the Bank. Yes. So he's told us you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did he ever do any part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
No. Just done the work, 'cos it was nine til - eight 'til five - in the London Dock. At times he done a bit of overtime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Was he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 ever off}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673  work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 No. In 
1911 - he - he come out on strike with the others, he was a regular man, and he lost his regular job, because permanent men wasn't allowed to come out on strike. See. No. He come out on strike with the others, of course he lost his regular job. But he got
 - he was always at work every day and paid every night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 You remember seeing the dock strikes do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh yes. Yes. 1911, 12, 13, nearly 14. Used to have one every year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Were they very violent, those strikes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes. Yes. Just the same as all the others you know. They do it in turn.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about your mother, do you know where she came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Yes, me mother was born in London here. And she always went to office cleaning. And my sister got killed over in that building there. They use
d to work in the East Indian Avenue, near Liverpool Street, and work there for a number of years. And me - me mother died when she was eighty-two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 When was that, quite a long time ago?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes. A long time ago, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Was she alive in the second world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh no. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did she always work after she was married, your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes, she always went to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
What about when she had the children, what would she do then when you were very small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Well - they used to go of
f to these offices where she worked, 'cos she worked in the East India Dock - East Indian Avenue for a decent number of years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 I suppose there was quite a lot of you wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 The older ones by that time probably could look after the younger ones?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 That's right. Yes. Look after them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What sort of hours would she be away, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Yes, she used to go - she used to go at seven in the morning, and come back at half past ten. And in the winter months when the ba
ths was running, that was the worst time, because they had to do the fires and then clean the jup ready for next morning. Well she wouldn't get done 'til about eleven o'clock at night then. And they used to get about a pound a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 For those long hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Very hard life wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
It was, yes. But though really and truly, me mother, she was very quick you know in walking, as I told you me sister had died - got killed over there - they both worked together for years, they did, alwa
ys together. Yes. 'Course she lost her husband, he was a - he worked for - Sainsbury's, provisions people, in one of their shops. But he - he dropped dead in - the court here at the top of the street, coming home. Then she was a widow for years, she never
 married again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 How many rooms did your family have when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Well we had - four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What was that, you'd have a kitchen would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Kitchen. Well the - the kitchen's in the room - itself, and you had three rooms behind that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 You'd use the other rooms for sleeping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Sleeping, yes. Used to be - you had one with a cot in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did you ever have any relations or people staying with you, any lodgers?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Just your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Just the family used to come and see you you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did your mother ever pay anyone to do any jobs in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
No. We couldn't afford it, no, no, no. 'Cos she - yes, she done her work, when she come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about your washing, would that be done at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Me mother used to all be home, me mother always done our washing. Always. 'Cos we had a wash house here, yes. 'Cos in - here from there, number seven and number ten, the wash house used to run back there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 You had a wash house here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh
 yes, had a wash house, of course they're on - they're on the wash house, number seven and number ten. See. And we had the wash house there, you used to have your turn, take your turn and so - took it in turns to do your washing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Was this hot water or cold?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 We made our own hot water, in a boiler. No, in a boiler.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 There was a boiler there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Yes. Yes. A boiler there and - the old fire underneath, to make your fire and hot up your water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 And people would take it in turns?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about clothes, would your mother make any of your family's clothes?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
No, she wasn't - no, she'd always, 'cos things was reasonable if you could afford it those days to buy, you know. But - she never made nothing. Well she never had no t
ime. By the time she got us all ready for school, one thing and the other - we got ourselves ready for school, well we wouldn't see her because she never come home 'til half past ten at night, we'd be at school, and - she would - she used to come maybe at
 twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did you have new or would you ever have second hand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh no. No, always had new.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Where did you buy clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Well - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Watney Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mile End Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or anywhere like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Was there any special time you had new clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 No, I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 You just had them when you needed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 When we needed them, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about shoes, would your father ever make or mend shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 No, I - no, we used to send them to the menders. And I used to go to a Jew
 man - round in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Back Church Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 with mine, and I used to wait for him - to do 'em. Soles and heel 'em, and while I was there, I used to watch him. And when I got married I used to do the children's shoes meself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Used to watch how he did them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 So isn't that difficult then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
It was, it was hard job because I've come - you see, I've come home from work on Saturday, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 missus\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673  say - 'course we was married fifty year - and - we - she'd say, Bill, so and so's - shoes are poor. I'd s
ay, oh I didn't know that love. Used to go up - Cable Street, buy off the Jews, you'd buy the stuff, fetch it back, and my mother we had a big kind of a trunk of a tree, about that height and that thick, hold it there, then mother brought me the last, the
 hammer and all the material, and I started - doing the boots for the children - the shoes for the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Your father didn't ever do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 No. No, he never done that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did your father ever help in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Like washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
No. Those days they wouldn't do it. Yes. Different to what they are today. Never done that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about things like lighting fires, would your father light the fire?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh he'd light the fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 That was a man's job was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about decorating, did he ever do any decorating or repairs in the house?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
No. No. No, he was a bad decorator, so - me mother used to do - you know, a little bit here and there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would your father ever help with the children, w
ould he ever dress them or undress them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Oh no. Well I don't remember that 'cos being youngest one in the family - never no recollection of helping like that. Though he was good at - as he was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would he ever read to you or tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Oh he'd tell - tell me stories and - another thing - when he come home from work - 'course he did like his little clan. And I used to say, I'd say, dad you stopping in tonight? He'd say, yes. Yes Bill. I'd take his boots off. And I'd go and get his Even
ing News, and I always remember - Evening News those days was ha'penny. And I used to go along the - top of the street, along another street and the man give me two. And I was so pleased he give me two, you know. So he said, now Bill, you take one back. I
 took the other one back. Yes. Very honest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would he ever take you out alone, without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Oh well - yes - he - as I say, he was a dockie, and he used to say to me, Bill - you haven't had half a day off for a long time now. And he'd get -
 say half a day off from the docks - and we used to go and sit - watch the - see the extra turns - at one of the - say the Forresters, Cambridge Road. Or was it the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Shoreditch, music hall, and they used to have extra turns there on a Thursday. A
nd I always recollect you know, and he was good - he was good by - at heart, and good by nature. I know meself in those days - the corner of the street, Wilmer Street and Dock Street, he'd give about eighteenpence away by the time we walked up to the top 
o
f them streets. Hello Jack, who's - well that's the boy. Here you are - tuppence you know. And I always remember - my father saying to me, he says, Bill, he says, you know that man I just spoke to? I said, yes. He said, now when you go out to work always 
keep your hands to yourself. Don't touch anything. Now that man got a month's hard labour - for knocking off a tin of sardines. I always remember that. Am I speaking loud enough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did your father say there was a lot of stealing in the docks at that time?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Yes, there were yes. Yes. Yes, he always said to me, he said, Bill, always keep your hands to yourself. He said, now that man got a month hard labour for knocking off - two sardines valued - at tuppence ha'penny. Yes, I always remember that. And I 
always remember we was in there once - on a Thursday and - the old \{BLANK\}
 you know used to come, because it was only tuppence to go in. Excuse me. And there was a fireman. Oh I was thinking to myself, this'll be good. And they let 'em - sing a little bit,
 then all of a sudden a man from Spitalfields meat market - food market - they'd be there with their oranges and - apples and one thing and the other, then they'd shie the - things on the stage. And I always remember this cos them curtains was very heavy,
 
curtain come down one side, knocked the old fireman - one way, knock - knocked him the other way, the other side, I remember that. So of course I was taking pity on the poor old fireman, you know. And - I - thought to myself well that aint right, because 
they used to go up there for a laugh. These chaps from Spitalfield meat market - fruit market. Yes, I always remember that one. Yes, he used to take me occasionally on a Thursday you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Up there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did you ever have any jobs you had to do at home to help your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Oh yes, on Saturdays it was always my job to do the knives and forks and spoons. With the old - whatsername, the old }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 brick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673  - brick dust. Yuh. Yes. Scrape it off in a - in a saucer, then wet it and then clean it up and wash 'em afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about your brothers and sisters, did they have to do anything to help?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
They was - out - well eventually me brother - last brother - Bert he got married, 'cos he lived here in I block, and he had a big family. And they eventually got married and me sister got married, and I was left there on me own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Did your older brothers or sisters have to help with the younger children at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Used to help, yes. You know, just help to get them ready for school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about taking them out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Then they - you'd go out for a walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Do you remember when you were young being taken out by any of your brothers or sisters
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
No. Well occasionally me father used to take me out of a Sunday. We used to go from here, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Dock Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} with t
he old horse trams. It used to be threepence return - to Stamford Hill, and back. He used to take me out for a ride of a Sunday. Because I'd come home, he'd go round to the pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 He took you because you were the youngest did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh I was the youngest one of the family, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
No. 'Cos we me mother wasn't done 'til half past ten as I say in the winter months it was eleven o'clock, you know, we used to wait up for her to come home. But always had the old fire. Yes, sit round the fire on the cold night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh yes, put ourselves to bed. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did you share a bedroom with anyone or a bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Me sister. When I was young I was with 
me sister and - when we got older we - me mother parted us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
What were your sleeping arrangements for your family, how many bedrooms would you use?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 We had three bedrooms. Yes. And a kitchen. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Where would you have your meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 In th
e kitchen. Yes, all in the one you see, the cooker there and - well wasn't a cooker those days, it was the old - stove. Yes. And of course that was twenty-one pieces in that. And my mother used to clean that, I always remember the number of them, twenty-o
n
e - pieces. Used to come up nice when it was done. Of course we had a hot water thing over there but of course we never used it - for water, only like for washing up water or anything like that. Not for making tea. And we had two old - stewing pots. And m
e mother - 'cos we always liked stew, my sister and I. And me - me mother used to make a lot of stews you know for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Do you remember what time you'd have breakfast when you were a little boy?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes, well round about - of course we used to go to s
chool at - quarter to nine. And round about - seven I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did your father have breakfast with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
No, he'd - just have a cup of tea or something to eat and then he'd - hop off to work at quarter to eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would he have anything to eat down at the docks do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
He'd have a cup of - well he - he used to work - drive a crane down there, and - they'd send - a lad out - for a bottle of tea, like a milk bottle - bottle of tea in the coffee shop, and he used to give the lad a penn
y when he come back with that. 'Cos they were never allowed - not like they are today - do as they like kind of things, walk out and walk back. Nobody don't you know you were there or anything else. Oh yes, and they was always there at their post.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would your mother be there at breakfast time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 She - she'd come at half - no, she'd be gone to work. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 So who'd get your breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Me sister. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Do you remember what you had for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Well - toast or something like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about Sunday breakfast, was that ever different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Well that - yes, and me mother - I always remember me mother, I used to like the rasher and tomatoes, that was when we was on our own, the three of us, you know, me father, me moth
er - and - and meself. They - if I hadn't have went to school, if I didn't feel well or anything like that, she'd always - because there was four shops over there on that court, where that block of flats is now. Bolts - the provision people. And a man who
 used to mend the boots and a greengrocer, Bob Bruce. And she used to go in there and buy a rashers and tomatoes those days was only - tuppence a pound. And I always remember - we used to get them foreign tomatoes, like the egg }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 shaped}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673  tomatoes. Yes. I could
 sit on the doorstep and eat half a pound of them. And she'd buy those you know, we'd have rasher and tomatoes. But I always remember - the bacon used to smell lovely. Different from what it did today - to today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Perhaps that was to do with the curing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes. Yes. I always remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 It was really appetising?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
It was really. Yes. She'd say, here you are Bill, it's all ready, sit down. Say, all right mum. Sit down have that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about lunch, who would be here for dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Me
 mo - well - the girl - Ethel, she come home to dinner, she worked at - Godfrey Phillips, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Commercial Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And she come home to dinner. 'Course the others had the - had their dinner out. Had something to eat until they come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Your father would have something to eat out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
He would - no, he would come home at twelve o'clock. And go back about quarter to one
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would you have a cooked meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes, we had a cooked meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What sort of things would you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh well - any - anyt
hing me mother could get hold of you know. Chops or anything like that, she might buy a small joint if it's - reasonable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 At weekends, did you have anything special on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh yes, we always had a good dinner on Sunday. Better tea.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did you have a special tea on Sunday as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes. We had - good tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What would you have to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Well we - me mother used to buy a bit of pork. Baked potatoes, greens. Then we'd have the afters. And me mother was always one of making bread p
udding. Yes, she was good, she always had plenty of bread over. And she never wasted none. And always made a good bread pudding. And the wife, rest her soul, she was her second best. She could make a good one. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would you have another meal when you came in in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Might have - couple of eggs or anything like that, that's what it'd be, yes. 'Cos eggs was reasonable those days. Yes. They was cheap. You'd get - a dozen for a shilling I think, years gone by.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Your mother was obviously a good manager was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 She was, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What do you think your father would earn, when you were about seven or eight?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Well - he - he used to get fivepence an hour - at the docks. For eight hours, eight or nine hours. That'd be about - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 So he'd only earn about four shillings a day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 That's all - oh yes, about four or five shillings a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Round about a pound or a bit more a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 I suppose if a woman was quite good at budgeting the family could manage?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
It was all right. Me mother was, rest her soul, she was good - manager, she knew what to buy, and she was always with me sister, that I remember, that - the one got killed over there, was always together and always went out and bought together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did your mother ever bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 No. No, never baked her own bread, always had the - from the bakers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did she make jam or bottle fruit?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 No, she wouldn't make jam nor nothing like that. She'd buy that in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would she make pickles or wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about medicines, did she ever make any medicines for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
No. We had - me mother - also the wife - me mother used to make me take two Beacham's pills every Saturday. Because I always remember her words, 
she'd say to me, Bill - now, they always clean an engine in a factory once a week. And your inside have to - be the same. So I said, all right, and she always give me - Saturday night give me - last thing give me two Beacham's pills. But the wife - when w
e had 'em all young, she used to buy senna pods, and put it in their tea. She used to tell me, say, Bill - put some senna pods in their tea. But - isn't that a funny taste mum tea? She says, I can't see nothing, it's quite all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Have they got a strong taste?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Yes. They could tell. Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, she would see that their bowels was kept open you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Was there anywhere for growing anything round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 No. No, nothing at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would you ever eat any tinned food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Tinned
 fruit? No, not - vegetables 'cos they was cheap you know, potatoes cheap, five pound for sixpence. And - she never bought no - she bought tinned fruit, oh yes she bought that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What sort of fruit did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Well you could buy - pears or anything like that, or apples. Years ago.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 What about dried fruit, did you ever have any dried fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes, dried fruit. They used to - there used to be some shops in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cable Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, 'course {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cable Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 was alive with shops. Yes, oh lovely shops they we
re. Oh terrible. Well I tell you it was only after the first war - it got a bit bad, but the second war, after the second war it got worse. Because half of these foreigners never went back. They stopped here. It was so god that they stopped here. But - wh
e
n I was younger - they was - Millbanks, a lovely butchers, go in there, buy everything, the old boy used to wear a straw hat - round one side you know, and - he would - be standing outside or inside the shop. And go in there and buy whatever you want. He 
u
sed to have save loys and pease pudding I recollect I used to go there, mother'd say, Bill, what about saveloys? Yes please mum. Say - and he used to stop open eleven o'clock at night. Yes, used to go with a big jug, saveloys and pease pudding and mother 
and I used to have it, knock it back between us. Yes. There then was Dawes', the provision people. That was a lovely shop that was, Charlie Dawes, I recollect his name, Charlie, his mother was a short sout}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673  person, his father was a big on the broad side. Lo
vely shop that was before, and there was the haberdashery shops. Cohen. Corner of - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Short Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes, there was plenty of shops there. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 Cats meat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673  shop for the cat. Pawn shop. Bells the - the oil people.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 It's really changed then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 You've really seen it, you've watched it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Yes. Tanners - Tanners used to be the pawn shop. Though of course me mother used to have to in and pawn several things you know, 'til the next weekend or - carry on for the week. Everybody done the same. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 How many times a week do you think you would eat meat in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Well - me - me mother used to - 'course we always had the old stew. But I'll tell you some - something about the stew. My sister Ethel and me, we never liked stew. Not - and - she
 said, Bill - 'cos we was good as like brother and sister, say, mum's got stew today. Well we used to go - oh dear or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 lord}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 ', down and get some - fish and chips, and say - mum, what have you got? Got stew. Oh - so she'd give us the money for fish and chips.
 You'd buy a penny piece of fish up there and penn'orth of cheaps for tuppence or threepence. And it was good. 'Cos we had one up the - no, one up the corner here was not one over there, but that used to be - oh I'll think of his name in a minute, Jew man
,
 used to be up the top just round by the tobacconist is now, that used to be the fish shop, two shops down Cable Street, one opposite that Church Lane, that used to be a smashing fish shop, and one the corner of - Shorter Street, and that was another one.
 
You'd get lovely pieces of skate like that for tuppence or threepence. And the chips were different to this bloke up here today, you buy chips up there for ninepence - I used to - yes - and nothing in it and - some are - warm and some are cold. I used to 
- go over there and buy - buy a bit of fish - since the wife, rest her soul - died, and - you'd pay - you never had no skate no plaice - he would - sorry it's too dear, can't afford it, kind of thing, and - \{BLANK\}
 Well - of course I haven't been out for tw
o months now 'cos of the old weayher. But I generally go to the shop - at the top there, Doll, we call her Doll, it's Harts, and - she - she - go over here, how's the fish bill? Oh I do not care about it So he said to me he said, I can't afford - well I d
i
d stop out of there. But the one at, she got me a beauty. And it was fried and fried all over again. Three or four times, yes. Yes. So - I thought to myself, well Bill, that's your lot. So now the woman at number nine, she gets me haddock, I tell her on t
he Thursday, I told her this morning, excuse me. Gets me haddock, and I have that for dinner. Well for dinner, say teatime I have it, well - about four o'clock I have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 that haddock}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 , and do that myself, sometimes I can do it all right and sometimes I can't. I
t's very funny, it is really. I had a plaice the week before last, the plaice turned out all right. And - of course I've seen this man when I've been waiting for the bus outside the Co-op, hello, you all right? I said, yes guv, I'm all right, I though to 
myself, well - don't want you - nothing at all to do with your - fish these days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 But do you remember when you were a boy you really enjoyed eating it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
We did, yes, really, and cracklings we used to buy. Well they used to give you cracklings for
 nothing. Yes. Bug paperful of - 'course they was very greasy you know, they were. And - well they'd give you them for nothing. But - I think the old - the old days was hard - everybody was more sociable, and you saw more - well like you might as well say
 saw more life. You take all the - stalls right along Moorgate there, you could buy anything. I used to go up with my father, meet my mother in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Leadenhall Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, and there was a pub over - the way, Herc - the Hercules. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Leadenhall Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I've seen m
e mother come out of there - they'd go in there and have a drink and come along Moorgate and me mother was always one for jellied easy. She like her jellied eels and they was only tuppence - or threepence a basin then. 'Course now they're about four or fi
v
e bob. And she'd stand there while me - I would with her, I'd have a basin, we'd stand there and me father be - in the pub, we used to call it the Long House - in Moorgate there, and he'd be in there and have a drink, then she'd go back and have a drink i
n the - in the pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Did you have any livestock as a boy, did you ever keep anything like rabbits?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Oh no. No. You couldn't, not in these buildings. OH no. No. No pets, no dogs. Well years gone by you see the children now - well I love to hear 'em,
 but you - see the children riding bikes around, that was never allowed. Cricket, football, we had - Holloway, the old porter, the old man, he lived in this block - and there was an old seafaring man, well I had a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 racquet}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 , a whatsname, and - you know -
 what do they call them - these - tennis racquet, and I had one of them. And they chased us, the pair of them, and I lost it and we never found it. Yes. But - you was never allowed - but still I do, I love to hear the children. But the only thing is on a 
- Saturday night, five o'clock, it's all dead here. You don't hear no children, I suppose they go up to listen to Doctor Who and one thing or the other and that's your lot. It's all quiet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Do you remember ever seeing your mother have less food so the r
est of the family could have more, would she ever go without at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh she had done occasionally, yes. Yes, I've seen a bit of that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
Would your father be given more than the others because he was the man earning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Oh no, no, he was very c
areful you know, he was always satisfied with what he had. Me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 mother would}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673  always try and - make up some afters or the other. What I used to like was the old - roly poly pudding. With the currants in you know, she'd make on the hob. She would make a big on
e of those. Yes. And we'd all - sit round had have it, and jam or tr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3610574\charrsid11870673 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 acle, whatever - of course she used to buy - those days - you could buy a ha'porth of treacle or a pennorth in the oil shop. I know - oh yes. Yes, loose. And jam as well. Yes. Then on the
