\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 
When they weren't actually doing their work what would they do with their spare time, if they had any spare time what would your father and mother do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4136265 WE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Well me mother n
ever had no spare time, 'cos she was at work, 'cos - in the winter time - manners - she'd work at - she worked - at East Indian Avenue, Leadenhall Street for years and years, and her my sister that died, rest her soul - in this block over here - was knock
e
d down - but - she never had no spare time. But me father - 'course he would get done, his tea would be all ready for him, and - I used to say to him, dad, are you going to stop in tonight? He'd say, yes Bill, I'd take his boots off, go out and get his pa
p
er at the top of the street round to the left, and - there used to be the Evening News those days used to be ha'penny, then went up to a penny and I recollect I brought two back. But he was very honest, he said, Bill, take that other one back. I had to ta
ke the other one back to the shop. My father was very honest but he did like his - his beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2764714 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1983454\charrsid11870673 Would he visit a pub regularly?
